{"sequence":81,"timestamp":"2026-04-24T10:55:05.965260339Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-4-973dcfd9","body":"`fix-now` High: exhausted per-member retries still bubble up as retryable stage failures. In [src/contexts/workflow_composition/final_review.rs](/home/user/ralph-burning/src/contexts/workflow_composition/final_review.rs:172) and [src/contexts/workflow_composition/final_review.rs](/home/user/ralph-burning/src/contexts/workflow_composition/final_review.rs:2390), `rewrite_transient_retry_exhaustion_error` preserves the original `FailureClass`, and `invoke_final_review_member` returns that retryable `TransportFailure`/`Timeout` after the member has already exhausted its own retry budget. The engine then sees that class in [src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs](/home/user/ralph-burning/src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:5844) and retries the entire `final_review` stage again. That turns a supposed per-invocation retry into compounded stage-level retries, multiplying backend calls and backoff delays. The changed resume test at [tests/unit/workflow_engine_test.rs](/home/user/ralph-burning/tests/unit/workflow_engine_test.rs:1227) now takes about 72s for exactly this reason. This violates the bead’s scope guard (`per-invocation transient retry, not per-stage restart`) and means an exhausted reviewer/arbiter failure is not actually terminal for the stage.","dedup_key":"b983a9997a820007a96fff5cd66a2bd5513317cfe40095283f29eca79c095ae1","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260424065222","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
